definition: "Prolactin is a single-chain polypeptide hormone synthesized and secreted by lactotroph cells in the anterior pituitary gland. It is structurally related to growth hormone and shares some signaling properties. Prolactin is primarily known for its role in initiating and sustaining lactation after childbirth — it stimulates mammary gland development and milk production. However, prolactin receptors are expressed throughout the body, including in the gonads, immune cells, liver, kidney, adrenal cortex, and brain, reflecting prolactin's diverse physiological roles beyond lactation. Prolactin secretion is tonically inhibited by dopamine released from hypothalamic neurons — unlike most pituitary hormones, which require a stimulatory releasing factor, prolactin is held in check by inhibitory dopamine tone. When dopamine signaling is disrupted — by pituitary tumors, certain medications, or hypothalamic disease — prolactin rises. This negative dopamine regulation explains why many medications that block dopamine receptors (antipsychotics, some antidepressants, antiemetics) are among the most common causes of elevated prolactin."
why_it_matters: "Prolactin is the most overlooked hormone in standard longevity and optimization panels — it is rarely included in routine hormone workups despite being a significant and treatable cause of low testosterone, sexual dysfunction, infertility, and mood disturbance in both men and women. Hyperprolactinemia (elevated prolactin) suppresses the hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal (HPG) axis through inhibition of GnRH pulsatility, leading to reduced LH and FSH, which in turn reduces testosterone production in men and estrogen/progesterone production in women. In men, this presents as low libido, erectile dysfunction, fatigue, reduced muscle mass, and infertility — a syndrome that is clinically indistinguishable from primary hypogonadism (low testosterone from other causes) unless prolactin is measured. In women, hyperprolactinemia causes irregular periods, anovulation, infertility, and galactorrhea (inappropriate milk production). Because the symptoms of hyperprolactinemia are nonspecific and overlap entirely with other hormonal conditions, it is systematically missed when prolactin is not included in the panel. For men and women on hormonal optimization protocols, prolactin testing is particularly important — understanding whether hormonal dysregulation stems from the pituitary versus the gonads determines both diagnosis and treatment."

standard_range: "Men: 2–18 ng/mL · Women (non-pregnant): 2–29 ng/mL · Pregnancy: up to 400 ng/mL"
